00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:29.650
PROFESSOR: Before I
continue with the material,

00:00:29.650 --> 00:00:34.830
I want to show you at least
the title of a recent paper

00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:39.260
in Nature, because it's
related to material

00:00:39.260 --> 00:00:41.450
we have covered in this course.

00:00:41.450 --> 00:00:44.630
It's about the Kerr
effect, the effect

00:00:44.630 --> 00:00:49.520
that one photon can create a
phase shift for another photon.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:52.540
And one goal, of course,
for quantum computation

00:00:52.540 --> 00:00:55.310
where things are
about single photons

00:00:55.310 --> 00:00:58.760
is to have a
single-photon Kerr effect

00:00:58.760 --> 00:01:01.800
that one photon can change
the phase of the other photon

00:01:01.800 --> 00:01:03.390
in a strong, noticeable way.

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:05.750
So maybe one photon should
create a phase shift

00:01:05.750 --> 00:01:07.620
on the order of pi.

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:11.760
And this was reported
here in this paper.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:17.960
Of course, the non-linearity
created by nonlinear crystals

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:21.850
is much too weak for that.

00:01:21.850 --> 00:01:28.176
But what those authors did is
they used microwave photos,

00:01:28.176 --> 00:01:30.330
had microwave photons
into cavities.

00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:34.320
And they were coupled
through a sapphire substrate

00:01:34.320 --> 00:01:36.330
with a Josephson junction.

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:38.840
So the non-linearity
here is the non-linearity

00:01:38.840 --> 00:01:42.390
of a Josephson junction,
which is actually

00:01:42.390 --> 00:01:45.260
realized with a
superconducting qubit.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:47.394
I can't explain you
many more details,

00:01:47.394 --> 00:01:48.810
but I just thought
it sort of cool

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:53.122
to see how the Kerr
effect, which we discussed

00:01:53.122 --> 00:01:54.830
and which we discussed
for single-photon,

00:01:54.830 --> 00:01:59.770
is realized, at least
in the microwave domain.

00:01:59.770 --> 00:02:03.290
And also, just sort
of to illustrate

00:02:03.290 --> 00:02:09.220
that I hope this course enables
you to read recent research

00:02:09.220 --> 00:02:11.630
papers, what those
people measured

00:02:11.630 --> 00:02:14.680
is a [? key ?] representation.

00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:16.750
This is a coherent state.

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:19.800
And then they showed, and this
is the subject of the paper,

00:02:19.800 --> 00:02:22.980
that the coherent state which
has a well-defined phase,

00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:26.470
lost its phase through
the Kerr medium.

00:02:26.470 --> 00:02:29.450
And you clearly see there
is a big phase uncertainty.

00:02:29.450 --> 00:02:33.460
But then after certain
time-- this is experiment

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:36.380
and this is simulation--
there is a re-phasing,

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:38.030
and the phase is back.

00:02:38.030 --> 00:02:40.280
There is a revival of
the coherent state.

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:45.030
All right.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:07.370
Now I want to address
one question which

00:03:07.370 --> 00:03:11.410
Cody asked about the g2
function and fluctuations

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:14.140
of single-mode light.

00:03:14.140 --> 00:03:15.630
Let me just summarize.

00:03:15.630 --> 00:03:20.880
I told you that if you
do the thermodynamics

00:03:20.880 --> 00:03:24.010
of a single mode, we find
Bose-Einstein distribution

00:03:24.010 --> 00:03:25.860
of photons.

00:03:25.860 --> 00:03:28.870
And we have a
thermal distribution.

00:03:28.870 --> 00:03:32.270
And a thermal distribution means
sometimes we have more photons,

00:03:32.270 --> 00:03:34.480
sometimes we have less
photons, depending

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:36.150
on the thermal distribution.

00:03:36.150 --> 00:03:39.810
And when we calculated what the
intensity fluctuations were,

00:03:39.810 --> 00:03:44.290
we found they're characterized
by a g2 function of 2.

00:03:44.290 --> 00:03:45.750
OK.

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:48.810
Then a little bit later
in this course-- actually,

00:03:48.810 --> 00:03:53.180
just this week-- I told you
that single-mode light always

00:03:53.180 --> 00:03:55.470
has a g2 function of one.

00:03:55.470 --> 00:03:58.630
And what I meant here is the
following, rather trivial.

00:03:58.630 --> 00:04:02.420
If you have a single mode,
that means that you [? align ?]

00:04:02.420 --> 00:04:05.620
[? it ?] is simply
e to the i omega t,

00:04:05.620 --> 00:04:07.130
the intensity is constant.

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:13.170
There are no intensity
fluctuations.

00:04:13.170 --> 00:04:16.950
And also, because everything
is sort of predictable,

00:04:16.950 --> 00:04:20.589
it's just one wave.

00:04:20.589 --> 00:04:24.790
The Gn function
factorizes into-- can

00:04:24.790 --> 00:04:26.870
be re-expressed by
the g1 function.

00:04:26.870 --> 00:04:29.290
So therefore, this is
the most trivial case.

00:04:29.290 --> 00:04:31.120
But the question
now is, how do we

00:04:31.120 --> 00:04:34.700
reconcile those two statements,
that a single mode, e to the i

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:38.960
omega t, does not have
intensity fluctuations?

00:04:38.960 --> 00:04:40.950
Therefore, is a g2
function of one.

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:44.990
And our earlier treatment
about single-mode black-body

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:45.810
radiation.

00:04:45.810 --> 00:04:48.450
And of course, the
answer is, what

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:51.190
is the single mode
in one context

00:04:51.190 --> 00:04:54.310
is different from the single
mode in the other context.

00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:57.910
Maybe let me explain that.

00:04:57.910 --> 00:05:00.490
Let's just create an
ensemble of cavities.

00:05:00.490 --> 00:05:03.010
We put them in thermal
contact with a reservoir.

00:05:03.010 --> 00:05:06.270
And then we break the thermal
contact with a reservoir.

00:05:06.270 --> 00:05:09.230
Each cavity has now a
perfect single mode, e

00:05:09.230 --> 00:05:11.020
to the i omega t.

00:05:11.020 --> 00:05:14.470
But each cavity is filled
with a different photon number

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:17.730
according to the
thermal statistics.

00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:19.965
So therefore, if you
just look at one cavity,

00:05:19.965 --> 00:05:21.815
we find no intensity
fluctuations.

00:05:21.815 --> 00:05:23.850
The g2 function is one.

00:05:23.850 --> 00:05:26.360
But if you extend
the ensemble average

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:28.350
over all the
different cavities, we

00:05:28.350 --> 00:05:32.700
find that there are
fluctuations in intensity.

00:05:32.700 --> 00:05:36.900
Well, we can now
keep that in mind.

00:05:36.900 --> 00:05:38.970
But now we can say,
well, let's just

00:05:38.970 --> 00:05:42.960
take one cavity which is weakly
coupled to a thermal reservoir.

00:05:42.960 --> 00:05:45.040
And instead of looking
at the ensemble average

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:48.000
of many cavities, we look
at the long-time average

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:49.350
of this one cavity.

00:05:49.350 --> 00:05:52.770
And what will happen is thermal
photons will be created,

00:05:52.770 --> 00:05:54.250
will disappear, and such.

00:05:54.250 --> 00:05:57.040
So now this one
cavity fluctuates.

00:05:57.040 --> 00:05:59.070
But technically,
what that means now

00:05:59.070 --> 00:06:06.140
is it means that the
sharp mode of the cavity

00:06:06.140 --> 00:06:08.500
is interacting with
the environment,

00:06:08.500 --> 00:06:09.680
and it becomes broadened.

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:12.750
It has a broadening delta omega.

00:06:12.750 --> 00:06:16.110
And this can be
regarded as that we

00:06:16.110 --> 00:06:19.680
mix in modes of the environment.

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:23.070
So in that case,
strictly speaking,

00:06:23.070 --> 00:06:26.720
it's no longer a
single-mode cavity.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:30.050
So you have to
consider those things.

00:06:30.050 --> 00:06:35.090
And depending what point
of view you want to take,

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:36.470
you get the different result.

